04626nam a22005775i 9780226353159DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015027993  a97802263531597 a10.7208/97802263531592doi  a(DE-B1597)550121  a(OCoLC)1139892343  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aE184.A1bT465 2016 4aE184.A1 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a305.80097309/05122231 aTesler, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPost-Racial or Most-Racial? :bRace and Politics in the Obama Era /cMichael Tesler. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b3 halftones, 55 line drawings, 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Obama as Most- Racial -- tChapter 1. Racial Attitudes and American Politics in the Age of Obama -- tChapter 2. The Spillover of Racialization Hypothesis -- tChapter 3. The Obama Presidency, Racial Attitudes, and the 2012 Election -- tChapter 4. Racial Attitudes and Evaluations of Public Figures in the Obama Era -- tChapter 5. The Spillover of Racialization into Public Policy Preferences -- tChapter 6. Racial Attitudes and Voting for Congress in the Obama Era -- tChapter 7. The Growing Racialization of Partisan Attachments -- tChapter 8. The Expanding Political Divide between White and Nonwhite Americans -- tChapter 9. Conclusion: Racial Politics in the Obama and Post- Obama Eras -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tChicago Studies in American Politics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Barack Obama won the presidency, many posited that we were entering into a post-racial period in American politics. Regrettably, the reality hasn’t lived up to that expectation. Instead, Americans’ political beliefs have become significantly more polarized by racial considerations than they had been before Obama’s presidency—in spite of his administration’s considerable efforts to neutralize the political impact of race. Michael Tesler shows how, in the years that followed the 2008 election—a presidential election more polarized by racial attitudes than any other in modern times—racial considerations have come increasingly to influence many aspects of political decision making. These range from people’s evaluations of prominent politicians and the parties to issues seemingly unrelated to race like assessments of public policy or objective economic conditions. Some people even displayed more positive feelings toward Obama’s dog, Bo, when they were told he belonged to Ted Kennedy. More broadly, Tesler argues that the rapidly intensifying influence of race in American politics is driving the polarizing partisan divide and the vitriolic atmosphere that has come to characterize American politics. One of the most important books on American racial politics in recent years, Post-Racial or Most-Racial? is required reading for anyone wishing to understand what has happened in the United States during Obama’s presidency and how it might shape the country long after he leaves office.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEthnic attitudeszUnited States. 0aEthnic attitudes. 0aPolitics and government. 0aRace awarenesszUnited States. 0aRace awareness. 0aRace relationsxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226353159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226353159.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete e